{
  "texts": [
    "The use of the proposed optimal detection threshold, γ opt, notably enhances the achieved BEP performance compared to γ subopt, with the improvement becoming increasingly evident as δ increases.",
    "Furthermore, increasing the value of N can compensate for higher noise levels (i.e., smaller δ values).",
    "This trend is demonstrated by the enhanced performance achieved in high-noise conditions (for instance, δ = 0.3) with N = 70, relative to lowernoise cases (for instance, δ = 0.8) with N = 15.",
    "As depicted in Fig. 4(a), larger values of δ and N lead to a noticeable improvement in BEP performance.",
    "Since δ can be interpreted as the SNR in conventional communication systems, it explains the observed improvement in BEP performance as it increases."
  ]
}